{{Quote|Chiss don't invade the territories of others. We don't make war against even potential enemies unless we're attacked first.|Force Commander Mitth'raw'nuruodo, to Jorj Car'das|<ref name="Outbound Flight" />}}
The '''defensive-only doctrine''',<ref name="Outbound Flight" /> also known as the '''Ascendancy honor code''',<ref name="DNI">''[[Dark Nest I: The Joiner King]]''</ref> '''Chiss codes of conduct''',<ref name="UAA">''[[Ultimate Alien Anthology]]''</ref> or '''non-aggression laws''',<ref name="Thrawn">{{InsiderCite|113|Dark Forces: The Villains of Star Wars|Dark Forces: The Villains of ''Star Wars''}}</ref> was a law of the [[Chiss Ascendancy/Legends|Chiss Ascendancy]] that rendered first strikes in warfare illegal and punishable by [[Exile (punishment)/Legends|exile]].<ref name="DNI" /> Through the influence of the ruling [[Aristocra/Legends|Aristocra]] and the [[Chiss Academy]], Chiss society considered pre-emptive strikes taboo.<ref name="Enter">''[[Enter the Unknown]]''</ref> The law was in place [[Millennium/Legends|1,000]] [[Standard year/Legends|years]] prior to [[22 ABY/Legends|22 ABY]]<ref name="Date" /> and was one of the central tenets of [[Chiss/Legends|Chiss]] society.<ref name="SQ" />

The Chiss [[Force Commander]] [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Mitth'raw'nuruodo]], [[Core name/Legends|known as]] Thrawn, violated the law in [[27 BBY/Legends|27 BBY]], when he [[Battle for Outbound Flight|destroyed]] the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Republic]] [[Starship/Legends|starship]] ''[[Outbound Flight]]''. Thrawn convinced the [[Ruling Families/Legends|Ruling Families]] to allow him to retain his position, although he had still created enemies for himself. After violating the law again in [[Raid on an enemy ground installation|another conflict]] Thrawn was stripped of his rank and exiled to a [[Unidentified planet (Thrawn's exile)/Legends|planet]] on the edge of [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] territory, where he was collected by [[Voss Parck/Legends|Voss Parck]].<ref name="Vision">''[[Vision of the Future]]''</ref>

In [[22 ABY/Legends|22 ABY]],<ref name="SQ date">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' dates the events of ''[[Survivor's Quest]]'' to [[22 ABY/Legends|22 ABY]].</ref> the issue on preemptive strikes along with their defensive-only doctrine became a subject of strenuous debate among the Nine Ruling Families.<ref name="SQ" />

In [[36 ABY]], [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] considered the possibility that the Chiss Ascendancy had rejected the law in response to changing galactic circumstances, causing the [[Swarm War]] with the [[Killik/Legends|Killik]] [[The Colony|Colony]].<ref name="DNI" /> [[Darth Caedus|Jacen Solo]], aware of the Chiss policy on preemptive strikes, attempted to frame the [[Raid on Supply Depot Thrago|attack]] of a Chiss [[Supply Depot Thrago|supply depot]] at [[Thrago]] on the Killiks, hoping to incite a Chiss counterstrike.<ref name="DNII">''[[Dark Nest II: The Unseen Queen]]''</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
The Chiss law against first strikes was first mentioned in the novel ''[[Vision of the Future]]'', written by [[Timothy Zahn]] and published in [[1998]] by [[Bantam Spectra]].<ref name="Vision" /> It was identified as the "defensive-only doctrine" by Zahn's [[2006]] novel [[Outbound Flight (novel)|''Outbound Flight'']].<ref name="Outbound Flight" />

The law has a similar precedent in real-world political theory called the [[Wikipedia:Non-aggression principle|non-aggression principle]], a fundamental axiom in individualist philosophy.

